{{italic title}}
'''''Motsoalle''''' is the term for socially acceptable, long-term relationships between [[Sotho people|Basotho]] women in [[Lesotho]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2058560241.html|title=Never on Sunday With Grappa|last=Brown|first=Michelle E.|date=27 May 2010|work=Between the Lines|subscription=yes|access-date=19 June 2016|via=HighBeam Research}}</ref> ''Motsoalle'' can be translated from [[Sotho language|Sesotho]] loosely as "a very special friend."{{Sfn|Zabus|2013|p=43}} The word, ''motsoalle,'' is used to describe the other woman, as in "she is my ''motsoalle'';" and a ''motsoalle'' relationship describes the bond between the two women. ''Motsoalle'' relationships are socially sanctioned, and have often been celebrated by the people of Lesotho. These women's relationships usually occur alongside otherwise conventional [[Heterosexuality|heterosexual]] marriages and may involve various levels of physical intimacy between the female partners. ''Motsoalle'' relationships have, over time, begun to disappear in Lesotho.

== About ==
''Motsoalle'' relationships can first be formed between women during [[adolescence]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HK6sAgAAQBAJ&lpg=PT324&dq=motsoalle&pg=PT324|title=A Companion to Translation Studies|last=Spurlin|first=William J.|publisher=Wiley Blackwell|year=2014|isbn=9781118616154|editor-last=Bermann|editor-first=Sandra|location=|pages=|chapter=Queering Translation|editor-last2=Porter|editor-first2=Catherine}}</ref> Often, a ''motsoalle'' relationship was acknowledged publicly with a ritual feast and with the community fully aware of the women's commitment to one another.{{Sfn|Peplau|2001|p=7}} One anecdote about a  ''motsoalle'' relationship describes how one woman, [[Mpho 'M'atsepho Nthunya]], and her husband threw a party in the 1950s to celebrate her ''motsoalle''.{{Sfn|Munro|2012|p=150}} Nthunya's account of her relationship with her partner, Malineo, was described to [[anthropologist]] K. Limakatso Kendall in a book, ''[[Singing Away the Hunger: The Autobiography of an African Woman]]'' (1997).{{Sfn|Kendall|1998b|p=220}} Judith Gay is another anthropologist to document these relationships, and she discovered they were once very common.{{Sfn|Kendall|1998b|p=220}} Jason Sullivan describes a form of ''motsoalle'' relationships among school girls where it functioned like a type of "[[puppy love]]" or mentorship.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sullivan|first=Jason|date=17 June 2016|title=Eras in Education "Mummy-Baby" Relationships in 1950s Lesotho: Learning About Loving|url=https://www.voicemagazine.org/articles/articledisplay.php?ART=6951|journal=The Voice Magazine|volume=24|doi=|pmid=|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref> Other anthropologists who have described ''motsoalle'' relationships include [[Stephen O. Murray|Stephen Murray]] and [[Will Roscoe]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ferreira|first=Alberto José Viralhadas|date=July 2012|title='The Fate of Flesh': Post-Humanist Views of the Body and Gende|url=https://www.inter-disciplinary.net/critical-issues/wp-content/uploads/2012/06/ferreiravispaper.pdf|journal=Inter-Disciplinary.net|doi=|pmid=|access-date=22 June 2016}}</ref>

''Motsoalle'' relationships differ from a [[Western world|western]] perspective of [[queer]] or [[lesbian]] relationships. Women in ''motsoalle'' relationships "marry men and conform, or appear to conform, to gender expectations."{{Sfn|Kendall|1998|p=239}} Women in these relationships do not have a different [[Identity (social science)|social identity]] even though they are in a committed relationship with another woman.{{Sfn|Peplau|2001|p=12}} Women in ''motsoalle'' relationships also differ from western ideas of heterosexual female friends.{{Sfn|Munro|2012|p=150}} Researcher, William J. Spurlin, stresses that "it is important not to simply translate into [[English language|English]] 'M'atsepo Nthunya's use of the Sesotho word ''motsoalle'' [...] as ''lesbian''."{{Sfn|Spurlin|2006|p=62}} Nevertheless, Spurlin does state that "it might be possible to place ''motsoalle'' relationships on the lesbian continuum to discuss, debate, and imagine them theoretically as possible sites of lesbian existence, given the close emotional and intimate bonds between the women, but with the stipulation that the relationships not be reduced to western understandings of 'lesbian.'"{{Sfn|Spurlin|2006|pp=71–72}}

Part of the difference between a ''motsoalle'' relationship and a lesbian one is due to the Sesotho notion of sex.{{Sfn|Munro|2012|p=150}} Many of the [[Sotho people|Basotho]] people of older generations in Lesotho did not consider an act a [[Human sexual activity|sex act]] if one partner was not male.{{Sfn|Munro|2012|p=151}} Therefore, anything women did together was not considered sex, even if it involved erotic components. Because of the social situation in rural Lesotho and the lack of a concept of lesbianism, ''motsoalle'' relationships were once widespread, but not seen as an "alternative to heterosexual marriage."{{Sfn|Kendall|199b|p=221}} Nthunya described it like this: "When a woman loves another woman, you see, she can love her with a whole heart."{{Sfn|Nthunya|1997|p=69}}

As Lesotho became more [[Modernization theory|modernized]], those communities exposed to western culture were also more likely to become exposed to [[homophobia]].{{Sfn|Kendall|1998b|p=222}} Kendall hypothesizes that as Western ideas spread, the idea that women could be sexual with one another, coupled with homophobia, began to erase the ''motsoalle'' relationships.{{Sfn|Kendall|1998b|p=222}} By the 1980s, the ritual feasts that were once celebrated by the community for ''motsoalles'' had vanished.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Dickemann|first=Jeffrey M.|date=2001|title=Female Desires: Same-Sex Relations and Transgender Practices Across Cultures (Review)|url=https://muse.jhu.edu/article/31175|journal=Journal of the History of Sexuality|volume=10|issue=1|pages=122–126|doi=|pmid=|access-date=22 June 2016|subscription=yes|via=Project MUSE}}</ref> Today, ''motsoalle'' relationships have largely disappeared.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YGvp0LnYN7cC&lpg=PA8&ots=EPUawJ8fug&dq=motsoalle|title=Tommy Boys, Lesbian Men and Ancestral Wives: Female Same-Sex practices in Africa|last=Wieringa|first=Saskia|publisher=Jacana Media|year=2005|isbn=9781770090934|editor-last=Morgan|editor-first=Ruth|location=|pages=295–296|chapter=Women Marriages and Other Same-Sex Practices: Historical Reflections on African Women's Same-Sex Relations|editor-last2=Wieringa|editor-first2=Saskia}}</ref>

