{{Infobox University |name =University of Applied Arts Vienna |native_name =Universität für angewandte Kunst Wien |latin_name = |image =Uni für angewandte Kunst Wien Logo.svg |image_upright =1.35 |motto = |established =1867 |type =public |city =[[Vienna]] |country =[[Austria]] |students =c. 1,800 |undergrad = |postgrad = |doctoral = |staff =340 |rector =[[Gerald Bast]] |campus = |colors = |colours = |mascot = |affiliations = |free_label = |free = |website =http://dieangewandte.at }}
The '''University of Applied Arts Vienna''' ({{lang-de|Universität für angewandte Kunst Wien}}, or informally just ''Die Angewandte'') is an [[Art school|arts university]] and institution of higher education in [[Vienna]], the capital of [[Austria]]. It has had [[university]] status since 1970.
==History== The predecessor of the ''Angewandte'' was founded in 1863 as the ''k. k. [[Kunstgewerbeschule]]'' ('''Vienna School of Arts and Crafts'''),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dieangewandte.at/en/university/profile/history|title=History and educational assignment - From the Imperial Royal Arts and Crafts School to the "Angewandte" of Today|website=www.dieangewandte.at/en/university/profile/history|access-date=2018-07-25|language=en}}</ref> following the example of the South Kensington Museum in London, now the [[Victoria & Albert Museum]], to set up a place of advanced education for designers and craftsmen with the Arts and Crafts School in Vienna. It was closely associated with the ''Österreichischen Museums für Kunst und Industrie'' (Imperial Royal Austrian Museum of Art and Industry, today known as the [[Museum of Applied Arts, Vienna|MAK]]).
It was the first school of its kind on the continent. In 1941 it became an institution of [[higher education]]. 1941-45 it was called "Reichshochschule fuer angewandte Kunst",<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://austria-forum.org/af/AEIOU/Kunstuniversit%C3%A4ten/Kunstuniversit%C3%A4ten_english|title=Kunstuniversitäten (english)|last=http://austria-forum.org/|first=Austria-Forum {{!}}|work=Austria-Forum|access-date=2017-04-18|language=de}}</ref> and in 1948 was taken over by the [[Austrian state]] as an [[academy]]. In 1970 it was awarded the title of a [[university]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/Dokumente/BgblPdf/1970_54_0/1970_54_0.pdf|title=Federal Law Gazette of the republic Austria (Bundesgesetzblatt der Republik Österreich)|last=|first=|date=1970|website=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813191008/https://www.ris.bka.gv.at/Dokumente/BgblPdf/1970_54_0/1970_54_0.pdf|archive-date=2011-08-13|dead-url=yes|access-date=}}</ref> and in 1998 it was renamed the ''Universität für angewandte Künste'' (''University of applied arts'').
Famous artists such as [[Gustav Klimt]], [[Oskar Kokoschka]], [[Koloman Moser]], [[Vivienne Westwood]], [[Karl Lagerfeld]],Jean-Charles de Castelbajac, [[Jil Sander]], [[Pipilotti Rist]], [[Matteo Thun]], [[François Valentiny]], [[Hugo Markl]] and [[Stefan Sagmeister]] were part of the university's staff or student body. Today its faculty includes many distinguished artists and teachers, such as [[Judith Eisler]], [[Erwin Wurm]], [[Hartmut Esslinger]], [[Greg Lynn]], Wolf D Prix (of [[Coop Himmelb(l)au]]), [[Peter Weibel]] and the philosopher [[Burghart Schmidt]].
==Present== The university has currently ca. 1,800 students and c. 380 faculty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dieangewandte.at/jart/prj3/angewandte-2016/data/uploads/Universitaet/Berichte/Rechnungsabschluss_Pruefbericht_2015.pdf|title=Final report of accounts of the university, 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The students come from 70 different countries to study in the 29 disciplines of the school, structured in 60% Austrians, 25% Europeans and 15% from other countries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.uni-ak.ac.at/uqe/download/WB2015.pdf|title=Knowledge balance of the university, data from 2015|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The outcome of their processes is made public in ca. 200 exhibitions a year and a multitude of different events and other public presentations.
==Notable alumni== Notable alumni from the University are<ref>{{Cite book|title=Die Hochschule für angewandte Kunst in Wien und ihre Absolventen von 1970 bis 1995|last=Al Chihade|first=Elisabeth|publisher=Österreichischer Kunst- und Kulturverlag|year=1999|isbn=3-85437-183-7|location=Austria|pages=}}</ref> * [[Walter Bosse]] (1904–1979), modernist brass sculpture * [[Dorrit Dekk]] (1917-–2014), graphic designer, printmaker and artist<ref name="Guardian">{{cite news|last1=Games|first1=Naomi|title=Dorrit Dekk obituary|url=https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/2015/jan/07/dorrit-dekk|accessdate=18 January 2015|work=The Guardian|date=7 January 2015}}</ref> * [[Brigitte Kowanz]] (born 1957), artist * [[Matthias Laurenz Gräff]] (born 1984), artist * [[Hugo Markl]] (born 1964), artist * [[Pipilotti Rist]] (born 1962), visual artist * [[Felice Rix-Ueno]] (1893-1967), textile artist * [[Stefan Sagmeister]] (born 1962), designer * [[Stylianos Schicho]] (born 1977), artist * Eva Schlegel (born 1960), artist and professor at the [[Academy of Fine Arts Vienna]] * [[Pola Stout]] (1902–1984), textile designer<ref>{{cite news |last=Pope |first=Virginia |date= |title=Blends Color Harmonies Into Fine Garment Fabric |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9800E3DE1730E43ABC4F52DFB566838B659EDE |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=2016-03-09 }}</ref> * [[Ernestine Tahedl]] (born 1940), artist * Matthias Tarasiewicz (born 1979), curator and researcher * [[Erwin Wurm]] (born 1954), artist * [[Lisbeth Zwerger]] (born 1954), illustrator
